For AdN determination, 200 μL of prepared MoS2-NS/VNCs (5.03 × 10−4 M) was introduced to solutions at various AdN concentrations (5–100 nM), and then the solution was diluted with 10 mM PBS 7.4 buffer to 2.0 mL. The signal output values were calculated according to the relative absorption and PL intensity 1/[A-A0
                        ] and 1/[P-P0
                        ], in which A, P and A0, P0 represent the absorption and PL intensity of the MoS2-NS/VNCs solution in the presence and absence of AdN, respectively. For the limit of detection, i.e., LOD = K × SD/S (where K = 3), SD is the standard deviation of the blank solution and S is the slope of the calibration curve.

Different concentrations of AdN were added to the PBS buffer at physiological pH region 7.4 as the medium and the PL intensity restoration was measured to evaluate the sensitivity of the strategy. To achieve optimal sensing performance, MoS2-NS/VNCs based nano-system was prepared by using MoS2 nanosheets with a concentration of 80 μg/mL, which ensured the maximum quenching efficiency (97.6 %) and lowest background signal. Similarly, the effect of incubation time was further optimized. Regarding the PL intensity recovery kinetics, the best PL recovery efficiency obtained within 5 min when AdN was added into the mixture solution. Fig. 7
                        a shows the strong PL intensity recovery of up to 65.7 % of the quenched PL emission of MoS2-NS/VNCs at 525 nm with the increasing concentration of target AdN [65]. The strong affinity interaction between AdN and detached VNCs from the MoS2 nanosheet surface lead to the PL recovery. In this regard, AdN would specifically combine with the L-Cys template with VNCs capped on the surface of MoS2-NS to form an adenosylcysteine [66,67] due to its structural switching properties, which would lead to the elimination of MoS2-NS via π–π stacking interaction [27,68,69]. Eventually, L-Cys-templated VNCs was released along with AdN from the MoS2-NS system (MoS2-NS/VNCs). Moreover, the solution adding 100 nM of AdN gives the highest PL intensity. Furthermore, QY of MoS2-NS/VNCs solution in the absence and presence of AdN were also measured. The results showed that the QY increased from 0.38 % to 8.77 %, which supports the potential of MoS2-NS/VNCs@AdN in bio-imaging applications. PL measurements further confirmed the PRET-controlled detection of AdN. The lifetime decay profiles of VNCs at the optimized MoS2-NS concentration is obtained in the presence of AdN (Fig. S16). The plot was fitted with a biexponential function, indicating two dominated excitonic processes with nanosecond lifetime of PL. The lifetime of MoS2-NS/VNCs increased from τ1 = 8.20 ns, τ2 = 0.68 ns to τ1 = 10.48 ns, τ2 = 0.79 ns in the presence of 100 nM of AdN (Fig. S16). The original lifetime recovery tendency confirmed a significant hindrance in the flow of resonance energy from VNCs to MoS2 NS in the presence of AdN. The relative change in PL intensity at 525 nm with an increase in AdN concentration has been shown in Fig. 7b [70]. The emission intensity and efficiency could be fitted to the Benesi–Hildebrand equation 1/[AdN] concentration vs. 1/(P-P0
                        ) and correlation coefficient (R2 = 0.9912) as shown in Fig. 7c. The limit of detection (LOD) [71] for AdN with MoS2-NS/VNCs was found to be 29 pM in a linear range from 0–100 nM, which indicates that the VNCs adsorbed on MoS2-NS of the donor and acceptor species was promising with highly improved sensitivity (Fig. S17) [19,20]. To investigate the binding mode of the AdN to MoS2-NS/VNCs, a Job plot was carried out. As shown in Fig. 7d, the PL intensity at 525 nm was plotted as a function of molar ratio ([AdN]/([MoS2-NS/VNCs] + [AdN]), and a point of inflection was observed at the molar ratio = 0.5, which revealed that the coordination ratio of the MoS2-NS/VNCs and AdN is at 1:1 stoichiometry. The detection limit using MoS2-NS/VNCs against AdN concentration allows a better quantitative result than most previous detection methods (Table S1) [19–33,70].
